Step 1 — Login to GitHub
(Page 1 image)
Open browser
Go to
https://github.com
Click Sign In
Enter
Username / Email
Password
After login you will see GitHub Dashboard (same as image).
Step 2 — Search Existing Repo
(Page 1 second image)
In the search bar at top
Type:
argocd-example-apps
Open the repository:
argoproj/argocd-example-apps
Step 3 — Fork the Repository
(Page 1 third image)
Click:
Fork
Top right corner.
Then click:
Create Fork
Leave everything default.
Now the repo will appear in your GitHub account.
Example:
github.com/YOURUSERNAME/argocd-example-apps
Step 4 — Clone the Repo
(Page 2 image)
Click
Code
Copy the HTTPS URL
Example
https://github.com/YOURUSERNAME/argocd-example-apps.git
Now open Command Prompt / PowerShell
Run:
git clone https://github.com/YOURUSERNAME/argocd-example-apps.git
Now go inside folder
cd argocd-example-apps
Step 5 — Start Docker
(Page 2)
Open Docker Desktop
Make sure it shows
Docker running
Step 6 — Start Minikube
(Page 2 terminal screenshot)
Open PowerShell
Run
minikube start --driver=docker
Wait until it finishes.
You will see
Done! kubectl is now configured
Step 7 — Check Kubernetes Nodes
(Page 2 lower image)
Open NEW PowerShell (Run as Administrator)
Run
kubectl get nodes
Output should show something like
NAME       STATUS   ROLES           AGE   VERSION
minikube   Ready    control-plane   ...
Step 8 — Create Namespace
(Page 2)
Run
kubectl create namespace argocd
Output
namespace/argocd created
Step 9 — Install ArgoCD
(Page 3 screenshot)
Run
kubectl apply -n argocd -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/argoproj/argo-cd/stable/manifests/install.yaml
It will create many resources.
Step 10 — Check Pods
(Page 3 screenshot)
Run
kubectl get pods -n argocd
Wait until all pods show
Running
Step 11 — Port Forward
(Page 3 lower screenshot)
Open NEW PowerShell as Administrator
Run
kubectl port-forward svc/argocd-server -n argocd 8080:443 --address 0.0.0.0
Now keep this terminal running.
Step 12 — Open ArgoCD UI
(Page 3 bottom image)
Open browser
http://localhost:8080
You will see Argo Login Page
Step 13 — Get Admin Password
(Page 4 screenshot)
Run
kubectl -n argocd get secret argocd-initial-admin-secret -o jsonpath="{.data.password}"
Output will look like
b25LQUlSTkx3MGE1VWZVSQ==
This is Base64 encoded password
Step 14 — Decode Password
(Page 4 second command)
Run
[System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetString([System.Convert]::FromBase64String('b25LQUlSTkx3MGE1VWZVSQ=='))
You will get real password like
onKAIRNLw0a5UfUI
Step 15 — Login to Argo
(Page 4 image)
Enter
Username : admin
Password : decoded password
Click
Sign In
Step 16 — Create Application
(Page 5 image)
Click
+ NEW APP
Step 17 — Fill Application Form
(Page 5-6 screenshots)
Fill exactly like this.
GENERAL
Application Name
sock-shop
Project Name
default
SOURCE
Repository URL
https://github.com/Gibbous101/argocd-example-apps.git
Revision
HEAD
Path
guestbook
DESTINATION
Cluster URL
https://kubernetes.default.svc
Namespace
argocd
SYNC POLICY
Enable
☑ Enable Auto Sync
Leave others unchecked.
Step 18 — Create App
(Page 6 screenshot)
Click
CREATE
Now deployment will start.
Step 19 — Application Dashboard
(Page 7 screenshot)
You will see
sock-shop
Status : Synced
Step 20 — Edit GitHub Code
(Page 7 bottom image)
Go to your GitHub fork repo
Open
guestbook-ui-deployment.yaml
Change something like
replicas: 1
to
replicas: 3
Commit the change.
Step 21 — Check ArgoCD
(Page 8 screenshot)
Go back to
http://localhost:8080
Argo will automatically sync and update deployment.
You will see
Healthy
Synced
